It was established using the former palace built during the crown prince era by {{ill|Emperor Taishō|ja|大正天皇|12=draft}} on {{ill|1907|ja|1907|12=draft}} (Meiji 40) as the shrine building,<ref>[http://today.blogcoara.jp/natukashi/2008/02/no432-9144.html Nostalgic Beppu Tales: No432 Literary Walk] 今日新聞, February 18, 2008</ref><ref>[http://today.blogcoara.jp/natukashi/2009/02/no620-58b1.html Nostalgic Beppu Tales: No620 Postcard Feature] 今日新聞, February 3, 2009</ref> in the area of the former Beppu Park in Aoyama-chō. (This park – now the site of the Beppu Municipal Park tennis courts<ref name="oita-press_2018-07-20" /> and Aoyama Kindergarten<ref name="about" /> – had an area of 27.3 ha as of now,<ref>{{Cite web|和書|url=https://www.visit-oita.jp/spots/detail/4518|title=Beppu Park|work=Official Tourism Information Site of Oita Prefecture, "The Prefecture of Onsen"|publisher={{ill|Tourism Oita|ja|ツーリズムおおいた|12=draft}}|accessdate=2018-07-20}}</ref> whereas before {{ill|World War II|ja|第二次世界大戦|12=draft}}, Beppu Park was larger, approximately 35 ha at the time it served as the main venue for the {{ill|Beppu International Onsen Tourism Exposition|ja|別府国際温泉観光大博覧会|12=draft}} in {{ill|1937|ja|1937|12=draft}}.<ref>{{Cite web|和書|url=http://www.beppu.biz/kongetu4.htm|title=Great Beppu Park Plan|publisher=Beppu History Materials Digital Archive|accessdate=2018-07-20}}</ref>
After {{ill|World War II|ja|第二次世界大戦|12=draft}}, due to the {{ill|Shinto Directive|ja|神道指令|12=draft}}, the Onsen Shrine located within a public park on government land could no longer be maintained,<ref name="oita-press_2018-07-20" />, and its sacred object ({{ill|Sacred Object|ja|神体|1=Shintai|12=draft}}) and mikoshi ({{ill|Mikoshi|ja|神輿|12=draft}}) were enshrined at Hachiman Asami Shrine. Since then, both the opening proclamation ceremony of the {{ill|Beppu Hachiyu Onsen Festival|ja|別府八湯温泉まつり|12=draft}} and the mikoshi procession of Onsen Shrine have been held at Hachiman Asami Shrine.<ref name="about" /> The mikoshi, originally constructed in {{ill|1919|ja|1919|12=draft}} (Taishō 8), had suffered from decades of weathering and was subsequently repaired and restored, with its completion proclamation ceremony held at Hachiman Asami Shrine on {{ill|2007|ja|2007|12=draft}} (Heisei 19) {{ill|March 24|ja|3月24日|12=draft}}.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://kiji.i-bunbun.com/read/read.cgi?1174748400=117478705318193=1 |title=The "Main Role" of the Hachiyu Onsen Festival Gets a "Makeover" for the First Time in 88 Years |work=アイぶんぶんひろば |newspaper=大分合同新聞 |date=2007-20-03-25 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070330180826/http://kiji.i-bunbun.com/read/read.cgi?1174748400=117478705318193=1 |archivedate=2007-03-30 }}</ref>.
Furthermore, the shrine building dismantled after the merger was relocated to Kasuga Shrine in Seikechō, {{ill|Oita City|ja|大分市|12=draft}} – the building having been lost in the {{ill|Oita Air Raid|ja|大分空襲|12=draft}} in July {{ill|1945|ja|1945|12=draft}} (Shōwa 20) – and was used as its main hall. After a new main hall was constructed for Kasuga Shrine in {{ill|1967|ja|1967|12=draft}}, the former building has served as a storehouse for the mikoshi.<ref name="oita-press_2018-07-20" />
