After {{ill|World War II|ja|第二次世界大戦|12=draft|12=draft}}, due to the {{ill|Shinto Directive|ja|神道指令|12=draft|12=draft}}, the Onsen Shrine located within a public park on government land could no longer be maintained,<ref name="oita-press_2018-07-20" />, and its sacred object ({{ill|Sacred Object|ja|神体|1=Shintai|12=draft|12=draft}}) and mikoshi ({{ill|Mikoshi|ja|神輿|12=draft|12=draft}}) were enshrined at Hachiman Asami Shrine. Since then, both the opening proclamation ceremony of the {{ill|Beppu Hachiyu Onsen Festival|ja|別府八湯温泉まつり|12=draft|12=draft}} and the mikoshi procession of Onsen Shrine have been held at Hachiman Asami Shrine.<ref name="about" /> The mikoshi, originally constructed in {{ill|1919|ja|1919|12=draft|12=draft}} (Taishō 8), had suffered from decades of weathering and was subsequently repaired and restored, with its completion proclamation ceremony held at Hachiman Asami Shrine on {{ill|2007|ja|2007|12=draft|12=draft}} (Heisei 19) {{ill|March 24|ja|3月24日|12=draft|12=draft}}.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://kiji.i-bunbun.com/read/read.cgi?1174748400=117478705318193=1 |title=The "Main Role" of the Hachiyu Onsen Festival Gets a "Makeover" for the First Time in 88 Years |work=アイぶんぶんひろば |newspaper=大分合同新聞 |date=2007-20-03-25 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070330180826/http://kiji.i-bunbun.com/read/read.cgi?1174748400=117478705318193=1 |archivedate=2007-03-30 }}</ref>.
Furthermore, the shrine building dismantled after the merger was relocated to Kasuga Shrine in Seikechō, {{ill|Oita City|ja|大分市|12=draft|12=draft}} – the building having been lost in the {{ill|Oita Air Raid|ja|大分空襲|12=draft|12=draft}} in July {{ill|1945|ja|1945|12=draft|12=draft}} (Shōwa 20) – and was used as its main hall. After a new main hall was constructed for Kasuga Shrine in {{ill|1967|ja|1967|12=draft|12=draft}}, the former building has served as a storehouse for the mikoshi.<ref name="oita-press_2018-07-20" />
