It was established using the former palace built during the crown prince era by [[:en:Emperor Taishō|Emperor Taishō]] on [[:en:1907|1907]] (Meiji 40) as the shrine building,<ref>[http://today.blogcoara.jp/natukashi/2008/02/no432-9144.html Nostalgic Beppu Tales: No432 Literary Walk] 今日新聞, February 18, 2008</ref><ref>[http://today.blogcoara.jp/natukashi/2009/02/no620-58b1.html Nostalgic Beppu Tales: No620 Postcard Feature] 今日新聞, February 3, 2009</ref> in the area of the former Beppu Park in Aoyama-chō. (This park – now the site of the Beppu Municipal Park tennis courts<ref name="oita-press_2018-07-20" /> and Aoyama Kindergarten<ref name="about" /> – had an area of 27.3 ha as of now,<ref>{{Cite web|和書|url=https://www.visit-oita.jp/spots/detail/4518|title=Beppu Park|work=Official Tourism Information Site of Oita Prefecture, "The Prefecture of Onsen"|publisher={{ill|Tourism Oita|ja|ツーリズムおおいた|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Tourism Oita|qq=}}|accessdate=2018-07-20}}</ref> whereas before [[:en:World War II|World War II]], Beppu Park was larger, approximately 35 ha at the time it served as the main venue for the {{ill|Beppu International Onsen Tourism Exposition|ja|別府国際温泉観光大博覧会|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Beppu International Onsen Tourism Exposition|qq=}} in {{ill|1937|ja|1937|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/1937|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki link invalid}}.<ref>{{Cite web|和書|url=http://www.beppu.biz/kongetu4.htm|title=Great Beppu Park Plan|publisher=Beppu History Materials Digital Archive|accessdate=2018-07-20}}</ref>
After [[:en:World War II|World War II]], due to the [[:en:Shinto Directive|Shinto Directive]], the Onsen Shrine located within a public park on government land could no longer be maintained,<ref name="oita-press_2018-07-20" />, and its sacred object ([[:en:Shintai|Shintai]]) and mikoshi ([[:en:Mikoshi|Mikoshi]]) were enshrined at Hachiman Asami Shrine. Since then, both the opening proclamation ceremony of the {{ill|Beppu Hachiyu Onsen Festival|ja|別府八湯温泉まつり|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Beppu Hachiyu Onsen Festival|qq=}} and the mikoshi procession of Onsen Shrine have been held at Hachiman Asami Shrine.<ref name="about" /> The mikoshi, originally constructed in {{ill|1919|ja|1919|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/1919|qq=}} (Taishō 8), had suffered from decades of weathering and was subsequently repaired and restored, with its completion proclamation ceremony held at Hachiman Asami Shrine on {{ill|2007|ja|2007|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/2007|qq=}} (Heisei 19) [[:en:March 24|March 24]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://kiji.i-bunbun.com/read/read.cgi?1174748400=117478705318193=1 |title=The "Main Role" of the Hachiyu Onsen Festival Gets a "Makeover" for the First Time in 88 Years |work=アイぶんぶんひろば |newspaper=大分合同新聞 |date=2007-20-03-25 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070330180826/http://kiji.i-bunbun.com/read/read.cgi?1174748400=117478705318193=1 |archivedate=2007-03-30 }}</ref>.
Furthermore, the shrine building dismantled after the merger was relocated to Kasuga Shrine in Seikechō, [[:en:Ōita (city)|Oita City]] – the building having been lost in the {{ill|Oita Air Raid|ja|大分空襲|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Oita Air Raid|qq=}} in July {{ill|1945|ja|1945|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/1945|qq=}} (Shōwa 20) – and was used as its main hall. After a new main hall was constructed for Kasuga Shrine in {{ill|1967|ja|1967|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/1967|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to 1000}}, the former building has served as a storehouse for the mikoshi.<ref name="oita-press_2018-07-20" />
