After [[:en:World War II|World War II]], due to the [[:en:Shinto Directive|Shinto Directive]], the Onsen Shrine located within a public park on government land could no longer be maintained,<ref name="oita-press_2018-07-20" />, and its sacred object ([[:en:Shintai|Shintai]]) and mikoshi ([[:en:Mikoshi|Mikoshi]]) were enshrined at Hachiman Asami Shrine. Since then, both the opening proclamation ceremony of the {{ill|Beppu Hachiyu Onsen Festival|ja|別府八湯温泉まつり|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Beppu Hachiyu Onsen Festival|qq=}} and the mikoshi procession of Onsen Shrine have been held at Hachiman Asami Shrine.<ref name="about" /> The mikoshi, originally constructed in [[:en:1919|1919]] (Taishō 8), had suffered from decades of weathering and was subsequently repaired and restored, with its completion proclamation ceremony held at Hachiman Asami Shrine on {{ill|2007|ja|2007|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/2007|qq=}} (Heisei 19) [[:en:March 24|March 24]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://kiji.i-bunbun.com/read/read.cgi?1174748400=117478705318193=1 |title=The "Main Role" of the Hachiyu Onsen Festival Gets a "Makeover" for the First Time in 88 Years |work=アイぶんぶんひろば |newspaper=大分合同新聞 |date=2007-20-03-25 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070330180826/http://kiji.i-bunbun.com/read/read.cgi?1174748400=117478705318193=1 |archivedate=2007-03-30 }}</ref>.
Furthermore, the shrine building dismantled after the merger was relocated to Kasuga Shrine in Seikechō, [[:en:Ōita (city)|Oita City]] – the building having been lost in the {{ill|Oita Air Raid|ja|大分空襲|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Oita Air Raid|qq=}} in July [[:en:1945|1945]] (Shōwa 20) – and was used as its main hall. After a new main hall was constructed for Kasuga Shrine in {{ill|1967|ja|1967|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/1967|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to 1000}}, the former building has served as a storehouse for the mikoshi.<ref name="oita-press_2018-07-20" />
