It was established using the former palace built during the crown prince era by [[:en:Emperor Taishō|Emperor Taishō]] on [[:en:1907|1907]] (Meiji 40) as the shrine building,<ref>[http://today.blogcoara.jp/natukashi/2008/02/no432-9144.html Nostalgic Beppu Tales: No432 Literary Walk] 今日新聞, February 18, 2008</ref><ref>[http://today.blogcoara.jp/natukashi/2009/02/no620-58b1.html Nostalgic Beppu Tales: No620 Postcard Feature] 今日新聞, February 3, 2009</ref> in the area of the former Beppu Park in Aoyama-chō. (This park – now the site of the Beppu Municipal Park tennis courts<ref name="oita-press_2018-07-20" /> and Aoyama Kindergarten<ref name="about" /> – had an area of 27.3 ha as of now,<ref>{{Cite web|和書|url=https://www.visit-oita.jp/spots/detail/4518|title=Beppu Park|work=Official Tourism Information Site of Oita Prefecture, "The Prefecture of Onsen"|publisher={{ill|Tourism Oita|ja|ツーリズムおおいた|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Tourism Oita|qq=}}|accessdate=2018-07-20}}</ref> whereas before [[:en:World War II|World War II]], Beppu Park was larger, approximately 35 ha at the time it served as the main venue for the {{ill|Beppu International Onsen Tourism Exposition|ja|別府国際温泉観光大博覧会|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Beppu International Onsen Tourism Exposition|qq=}} in [[:en:1937|1937]].<ref>{{Cite web|和書|url=http://www.beppu.biz/kongetu4.htm|title=Great Beppu Park Plan|publisher=Beppu History Materials Digital Archive|accessdate=2018-07-20}}</ref>
