{{Infobox religious building|prefecture={{ill|Beppu|WD=Q273880|1=Beppu}}}} '''Onsen Shrine''' (温泉神社) is a {{ill|Shinto shrine|en|Shinto shrine|WD=Q845945|lt=Shinto Shrine|1=Shinto shrine}} that once stood in Aoyama-chō, {{ill|Beppu|en|Beppu|WD=Q273880|lt=Beppu City|1=Beppu}}, {{ill|Ōita Prefecture|en|Ōita Prefecture|WD=Q133924|lt=Oita Prefecture|1=Ōita Prefecture}}. It served as the guardian deity of one of the {{ill|Beppu Onsen|en|Beppu Onsen|WD=Q4890932|lt=Beppu Hachiyu|1=Beppu Onsen}}’s {{ill|Beppu Onsen|ja|別府温泉#別府温泉|lt=Beppu Onsen|lt_ja=別府温泉|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Beppu Onsen|1=Beppu Onsen|comment=changed title based on wikidata|WD=Q4890932}}, and after {{ill|World War II|en|World War II|WD=Q362|lt=World War II|1=World War II}}, it was enshrined together at the {{ill|Hachiman Asami Shrine|ja|八幡朝見神社|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Hachiman Asami Shrine|qq=}}, with the rites of Onsen Shrine continuing there.<ref name="about">{{Cite web|和書 |url=http://www.asami.or.jp/about.php |title=朝見神社について |publisher=八幡朝見神社 |accessdate=2018-07-23 }}</ref><ref name="oita-press_2018-07-20">{{cite news |url=http://www.oita-press.co.jp/1010000000/2018/07/20/JD0057123337 |title=温泉神社の意外な事実 かつての社殿は春日神社に |newspaper=大分合同新聞 |date=2018-07-20 }}</ref>.
The Onsen Shrine located in Tetsuwan, {{ill|Beppu|en|Beppu|WD=Q273880|lt=Beppu City|1=Beppu}} is not directly related to the Onsen Shrine (guardian deity of Tetsuwan Onsen) {{ill|Onsen Shrines|lt=Onsen Shrines|lt=Onsen Shrine|ja|温泉神社 (別府市鉄輪)|lt=Onsen Shrines|lt=Onsen Shrine|lt_ja=温泉神社|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Onsen Shrine|qq=}}.
== History == The tradition began when Hase Shrine, formerly in Asami, {{ill|Beppu|en|Beppu|WD=Q273880|lt=Beppu City|1=Beppu}}, enshrining the deity {{ill|Toshigami|en|Toshigami|WD=Q3028663|lt=Great Age Deity|1=Toshigami}} (god of abundant harvest) and Atago Shrine, enshrining the deity {{ill|Kagu-tsuchi|en|Kagu-tsuchi|WD=Q1640658|lt=Kagutsuchi|1=Kagu-tsuchi}} (god of fire), were merged in worship after receiving permission on {{ill|1919|en|1919|WD=Q2157|lt=1919|1=1919}} (Taishō 8) on {{ill|December 21|en|December 21|WD=Q2603|lt=December 21|1=December 21}}, and when {{ill|Ōkuninushi|en|Ōkuninushi|WD=Q276944|WD=Q276944|lt=Okuninushi|1=Ōkuninushi}} (the god of medicine) and {{ill|Sukunabikona|en|Sukunabikona|WD=Q3275687|lt=Sukunabikona|1=Sukunabikona}} (the god of water) were added, thus coming to be known as Onsen Shrine.<ref name="about" /><ref name="oita-press_2018-07-20" />.
